---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Type from "../../components/posts/Type.astro";
const pageTitle = "Tags";
const allPosts = await getCollection("posts");
const tags = [...new Set(allPosts.map((post) => post.data.tags).flat())];
---

<BaseLayout pageTitle={pageTitle}>
<main>
    <article>
        <Type typeTitle="alltags." routeTitle="tags" />
        <div class="tags">
            {tags.map((tag) => <a class="tag" href={`/tags/${tag}`}>{tag}</a>)}
        </div>
        <h2>main tags are</h2>
        <p>debug: finding interesting things and/or fixing them</p>
        <p>opinion: my view of things</p>
        <p>hardway: <strike>the next Battlefield games title</strike> analysing my own mistakes and failures</p>
        <h3>the rest are various tags depending on tech, level of expertise, etc.</h3>

        <p>we are not targeting devs here, or judge code quality. only my own.</p>
                
        <h3>Are you a student / junior, afraid of big corp tech? You can get to know them here. See what's behind their requirements.</h3>

        <p>Real production code. This way you can learn. Even if you're not working as a developer 8 hours a day. Reading real things or implementing real things is the only true way to progress as a programmer. </p>



        <h2>testing</h2>
        <h3>browsers</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Chromium / v8 - Chrome, Brave, Edge</li>
            <li>gecko / spidermonkey - FireFox, FireFox Dev</li>
            <li>webkit / javascriptcore - Safari</li>
            <li>android using chromium browser</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>OS</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>windows 11</li>
            <li>macOS latest whatever animal mountain name is the current one</li>
            <li>linux on an ubuntu 22.04 LTS</li>
        </ul>

    </article>
    <aside>
        <p>{tags.length} tags currently.</p>
    </aside>

</main>
</BaseLayout>

